    "draw": "You are the FIGURE DRAWER (Sonnet 5) for the web textbook \"The LLM Stack\".\nChapter (read the relevant sections for exact framing/terminology): /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/content/02-transformer/05-positional-encoding.md\n\nAuthor these figures. Do them ONE AT A TIME; finish and verify each before the next. Do NOT stop\nearly \u2014 complete every task or list what you couldn't in figures_skipped.\n\n  NEW  [static]  name=position-injection-sites\n       concept: The two sites where position can enter attention (Approach A: add to the representation; Approach B: add to the score) and RoPE as the hybrid that lives between them.\n       placement: after 'In the 'Why Attention Needs Position, and the Two Ways to Add It' section, replacing / upgrading the ASCII 'APPROACH A ... APPROACH B' text block.'\n       brief: A single left-to-right attention data path drawn once as a clean pipeline, with two clearly marked injection taps. Flow: token embeddings x_i \u2192 [Q,K,V projections] \u2192 score S_ij = (q_i\u00b7k_j)/\u221ad_k \u2192 softmax \u2192 \u00b7V \u2192 output. TAP A ('Approach A \u2014 add to the representation'): a downward arrow labelled '+ p_i' entering the x_i node BEFORE the projections; hang a small tag listing 'sinusoidal, learned absolute'. TAP B ('Approach B \u2014 add to the score'): a downward arrow labelled '+ bias(i,j)' entering the score node S_ij; tag 'T5 relative bias, ALiBi'. Then draw a visually distinct THIRD element for RoPE: a small 'rotate q,k' badge placed ON the Q and K lines between the projection and the dot product, with a callout box 'RoPE (hybrid): touches q,k like Approach A, but rotation makes q\u00b7k depend only on the offset i\u2212j, achieving Approach B\u2019s relative goal.' Include a compact legend keying three colors: A, B, RoPE-hybrid. Use the theme's accent tokens (color A, color B, and a highlight accent for RoPE); no hardcoded primaries. Enforce a clear single reading direction (left to right for the path, taps entering from above), keep every label legible and fully inside the viewBox.\n\nFIGURE AUTHORING SPEC (follow exactly \u2014 correct, beautiful, theme-safe):\nOUTPUT FILE: a self-contained figures/<NAME>.html: a `<figure class=\"viz\" id=\"fig-<NAME>\">` with\n  optionally `<button class=\"viz-replay\" type=\"button\">/replay</button>`, exactly one inline\n  `<svg viewBox=\"0 0 W H\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"...\">` (W ~ 660-820; H to fit), and a\n  `<figcaption>` with a <b>bold lead sentence</b> + 1-2 sentences on the takeaway.\n  No <script>, no external images. A scoped `<style>` (selectors prefixed #fig-<NAME>) is fine.\nLAYOUT: EVERYTHING inside the viewBox with ~10px padding \u2014 text must NOT run past edges (it clips).\n  No illegible overlaps (>= ~16px gaps between groups). Clear left-to-right or top-to-bottom order.\nCOLOR (must work in BOTH themes \u2014 NEVER hardcode a primary color): prefer classes v-fill, v-accent,\n  v-accent-s, v-stroke, v-grid, v-muted, v-label, v-mono; or inline `var(--accent)` /\n  `stroke=\"var(--good,#2f9e6e)\"`. Vars: --accent,--accent-2,--ink-soft,--muted,--good(#2f9e6e),\n  --warn(#e0a106),--accent2(#3b82f6),--surface,--surface-3,--border-2. Raw hex is FORBIDDEN as a\n  primary color (breaks one theme); hex allowed ONLY as the fallback inside var(...).\nFONTS: `font:600 13px var(--sans,sans-serif)`; code/labels `var(--mono,monospace)`.\nANIMATION (enhancement only \u2014 the figure MUST be fully clear as a STATIC image; never rely on motion):\n  stage reveals via `data-anim=\"1\"..\"5\"` on top-level groups; `class=\"viz-draw\" style=\"--len:NNN\"`\n  draws a line; `class=\"viz-sweep\"` sweeps; `class=\"viz-pulse\"` pulses. For a `long-animation`, use a\n  longer ordered sequence of data-anim stages that walks through the process step by step, but every\n  stage's end-state must still read correctly as a static frame.\nTEXT SAFETY: ASCII only inside the SVG (no fancy Unicode arrows/operators/emoji/math-alphanumerics \u2014\n  they tofu). Use ->, <=, x, pi, sqrt written out, etc. Small illustrative integers only; invent NO\n  benchmark numbers. role=\"img\" + a one-sentence aria-label.\n\nFor EACH figure:\n1. Write (NEW) or Edit (refine/replace) /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html per the brief and SPEC.\n2. VISUALLY VERIFY: `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook, then READ\n   /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Fix anything clipped, overlapping, low-contrast in\n   either theme, or that misrepresents the idea. Iterate up to 3 passes until both look clean.\n3. For a NEW figure, insert the marker `{{fig:<NAME>}}` on its own line (blank line before/after)\n   into content/02-transformer/05-positional-encoding.md at the planned placement, using Edit. Change NOTHING else in the chapter.\n   (refine/replace keep their existing marker \u2014 do not add a duplicate.)\n\nReturn the structured result: figures_done (names finished + verified) and figures_skipped (with why).",
    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/02-transformer/05-positional-encoding.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Bare attention is permutation-equivariant: it sees an unordered SET of vectors, so 'dog bites man' and 'man bites dog' are identical to it. Word order carries no signal unless we inject position ourselves.; There are exactly two places to inject position: Approach A adds to the representation (x_i + p_i, before attention), Approach B adds a bias to the pre-softmax score S_ij. RoPE is the hybrid: it touches q,k (A's locus) but is engineered so q\u00b7k depends only on the relative offset (B's goal).; RoPE rotates each 2-D feature pair by an angle proportional to its position; when you dot a query rotated by m\u03b8 with a key rotated by n\u03b8, the absolute angles cancel and only the relative offset (m\u2212n)\u03b8 survives.; Position is encoded as a SPECTRUM of rotation frequencies: d/2 pairs on a geometric ladder from fast (local, wavelength ~6 tokens) to slow (long-range, wavelength ~50k tokens). This same ladder underlies sinusoidal encodings and RoPE.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  position-injection-sites\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
