    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/02-transformer/12-diffusion-nonAR-lms.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: The latency win is a reduction in SERIAL DEPTH, not FLOPs: AR needs L sequential forward passes (one token per pass) while masked diffusion needs only N \u226a L parallel denoising steps that each process the whole sequence at once.; The forward process is absorbing masking (clean \u2192 progressively [MASK] \u2192 all [MASK]) with \u03b1_t = probability a token survives; the reverse-process training loss collapses to a mask-rate-weighted cross-entropy computed ONLY on masked positions \u2014 a continuous-time, order-agnostic generalization of BERT-style masked LM.; A single denoising step predicts all masked tokens CONDITIONALLY INDEPENDENTLY, which is wrong for language; iterative confidence-based remasking (commit the confident few, re-condition, repeat) recovers the inter-token correlations \u2014 more steps trade compute for coherence.; Block diffusion interpolates AR and diffusion: generate blocks left-to-right (block-causal mask, KV-cache reuse) but denoise the tokens WITHIN a block in parallel (bidirectional); block size B is the dial from pure AR (B=1) to pure diffusion (B=L), and enables flexible length.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  dllm-bidirectional-infilling\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
